# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: arnold-hills
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] The **1877 FA Cup final** was a football match between Wanderers and Oxford University on 24 March 1877 at Kennington Oval in London.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] It was the sixth final of the world's oldest football competition, the Football Association Challenge Cup (known in the modern era as the FA Cup).
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Wanderers were the reigning cup-holders and had won the competition three times in total.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Oxford had also previously won the tournament, making this the first FA Cup final played between two former winners.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Wanderers had reached the final without conceding a goal, defeating Cambridge University in the semi-finals.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Oxford had only played three matches in the five rounds prior to the final due to a combination of byes and opponents withdrawing.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Oxford took the lead in the final when Arthur Kinnaird, the Wanderers goalkeeper, stepped behind his goal-line while holding the ball, thereby scoring an own goal.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Wanderers equalised in the dying stages of the match and scored the winning goal in extra time.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Oxford's goal was struck from the official records after the match, but reinstated over a hundred years later.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Wanderers were the reigning cup holders and had also won the tournament in both 1872 and 1873.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Oxford University had won the competition in 1874.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Both teams entered the competition at the first round stage and were allocated home matches against Saffron Walden and Old Salopians respectively.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Neither match took place, however, as in each case the away team withdrew from the competition, giving their opponents a bye into the next round.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] In the second round, Wanderers and Oxford both scored six goals, defeating Southall and 105th Regiment respectively.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] In the third round, Wanderers beat Pilgrims 3–0 and Oxford again progressed without playing when their scheduled opponents, the leading Scottish club Queen's Park, withdrew.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Wanderers themselves progressed through the quarter-finals on a bye as an uneven number of teams remained in the competition.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Oxford were held to a goalless draw by Upton Park, but emerged victorious after a replay two weeks later.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] In the semi-finals Oxford received a bye, progressing straight to the final, and Wanderers beat the other of the great universities, Cambridge University, 1–0.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Both teams chose to play with two full-backs, two half-backs and six forwards, in keeping with the attacking style of play generally employed at the time.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Arthur Kinnaird played in goal for Wanderers, even though he had played as a forward in three earlier cup final appearances.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] At the time, the position of goalkeeper was not considered a specialised one, and players often alternated between playing in goal and playing in outfield positions.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] The game was played at Kennington Oval, home of Surrey County Cricket Club and took place in extremely bad weather, with rain and sleet hampering the players.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Wanderers won the coin toss and chose to begin the match defending the Harleyford Road end of the stadium.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] The Wanderers players began the game in relative disarray, which the correspondent from *The Sportsman* reported was not an uncommon feature of their matches.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] After fifteen minutes Oxford were awarded a corner kick, which Evelyn Waddington kicked high towards the goal.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Kinnaird caught the ball, but in doing so stepped behind the goal-line.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] The Oxford players immediately appealed for a goal to be awarded, and after a consultation the officials did so, giving the University team the lead.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Some time later, Charles Wollaston was injured and swapped positions with Kinnaird.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] At the time the concept of substitution had not been introduced to the sport, so injured players were obliged to remain in the game unless they were completely unable to play on, but it was common for an injured player to "retire into goal", where it was felt he would be less of a liability.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] As Wanderers pressed for an equaliser, Francis Birley took an indirect free kick, which went into the Oxford goal, but no goal was awarded as the ball had gone straight in without touching another player.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Four minutes from the end of the game, Hubert Heron made what *The Field* called a "splendid run" and passed the ball to Jarvis Kenrick, whose shot eluded Oxford goalkeeper Edward Alington to level the scores and send the game into extra time.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Seven minutes into the extra period, William Lindsay's goalbound shot was headed away by an Oxford player but the ball rebounded to Lindsay who sent it past Alington to give Wanderers a lead which the cup holders kept until the end of the game and thus retained the trophy.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] Some time after the match, Kinnaird informed the council of the Football Association (FA), of which he was a member, that in his opinion he had not carried the ball over the line for Oxford's goal.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] For the next century, all sources reported the score of the match as 2–0.
[src:arnold-hills/1877-fa-cup-final] In the 1980s, after fresh research into contemporary reports of the game by football historians, the FA reinstated the Oxford goal, and now regard the official final score of the 1877 final as 2–1.
[src:arnold-hills/1878-aac-championships] The **1878 AAC Championships** was an outdoor track and field competition organised by the Amateur Athletic Club (AAC).
[src:arnold-hills/1878-aac-championships] The championships were held on 15 April 1878, at the Lillie Bridge Grounds in London.
[src:arnold-hills/a-breeze-harper] Harper attributes her initial interest in practicing veganism to the influence of the work of Dick Gregory in connecting diet to the liberation struggle of marginalized groups, and to Afrocentric, raw foodist Queen Afua.
[src:arnold-hills/a-breeze-harper] In 2015, Harper organized a conference, *The Vegan Praxis of Black Lives Matters*, to discuss intersectional issues concerning veganism and the Black Lives Matter movement.
[src:arnold-hills/a-breeze-harper] In the same year, Harper joined the advisory board for *Black Vegans Rock*.
[src:arnold-hills/a-breeze-harper] Harper was the Humane Party's vice-presidential nominee for the 2016 U.S. presidential election.
[src:arnold-hills/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:arnold-hills/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:arnold-hills/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:arnold-hills/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:arnold-hills/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:arnold-hills/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner obtained his M.D. from Yale Medical School in 1909 and received the Campbell Gold Medal for the highest rank on his examination and the Keese Prize for his thesis.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] In 1916, Buttner was described by the editor of the *Journal of the American Medical Association* as a "recognized representative in the literature of vegetarianism." He argued for vegetarianism from a scientific basis.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner practiced medicine in New Haven, Connecticut.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] He was a member of the New Haven County Medical Association.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner is best known for his vegetarian book *A Fleshless Diet*, published in 1910.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] It was widely reviewed in medical journals with a mixed response.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner argued that comparative anatomy and nutrition demonstrates that man is suited for a fleshless diet and that meat is dangerous and unnecessary.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] His recommended diet consisted of vegetables, eggs and milk.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] Buttner wrote that "It is not illogical for vegetarians to use milk and eggs, as these animal products are distinctly less toxic than meat and also less likely to be disease-laden.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *American Physical Education Review*, praised the book for compiling useful dietetic research but commented that it failed to show scientific discretion in the selected material.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] A review in the *Journal of the American Medical Association* recommended the book as a reference work whether or not one accepts Buttner's conclusions.
[src:arnold-hills/a-fleshless-diet] A review in *The Medical Standard*, noted that the book was a "piece of special pleading for the propaganda which it is designed to promote […] We may say this, however, for Dr.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] In 1893, Cole prepared a set of vegetarian menus that received high commendation at the Universal Cookery Exhibition.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] The menus were later published as "Menus for a Week in November" in Rachel Swain's *Swain Cookery* and in Florence I.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] Nicholson's *The Jubilee Cookery Book: Vegetarian Recipes*.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] Cole worked in several London vegetarian organisations.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] Tovey in founding the Battersea, Clapham and Wandsworth Vegetarian Society, with A.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] She was a committee member of the Women's Vegetarian Union and gave a cookery lesson for the union at the offices of the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1898.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] According to James Gregory, Cole worked as an assistant to Nicholson and later to Charlotte Despard.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] She succeeded Nicholson as editor of *The Children's Realm*.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] By 1914, she was honorary secretary of the Vegetarian Federal Union.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] Cole gave public talks and demonstrations on vegetarian cookery.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] In 1910, as secretary of the West London Vegetarian Society, she gave a cookery demonstration at a vegetarian dinner held by the society at Pirbright Hall, Southfields.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] In 1913, as honorary secretary of the London Vegetarian Society, she spoke on "What is Vegetarianism" at a meeting at the Adult School in Sutton.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] In July 1915, *The Jewish Chronicle* published an interview with Cole, then secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, on vegetarianism and Jewish dietary practice.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] She argued that a vegetarian diet was compatible with Jewish religious observance and discussed food economy during the First World War.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] In 1917, when described as a former organising secretary of the London Vegetarian Association, she gave cookery demonstrations for the Food and Cookery Association in Southampton, where she presented vegetarian menus and methods for reducing food waste.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] Cole was listed as secretary of the Children's Dinner Fund in 1916.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] Hilda Kean writes that Nicholson established the fund for underfed children, distributing cheap meals of vegetable soup, wholemeal bread, and wholemeal currant bread.
[src:arnold-hills/a-m-cole] In 1921, Cole was honorary secretary and organiser of the Women's Freedom League Settlement in Nine Elms, which provided daily penny and halfpenny hot meals for more than 100 children and operated a milk depot.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] Alfred Owen Broadley was born on 7 July 1868 in Greetland, Yorkshire, to Owen and Elizabeth Broadley.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He was baptised on 6 September at St Thomas, Greetland.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] Broadley began his minister career with the Bible Christian Church at Salford from 1905 to 1917.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He was assistant preacher to James Clark at Cross Lane Church in Salford.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He worked as an engraver at Broad Oak Printworks.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He was appointed minister at Haliwell Road Unitarian Church in Bolton from 1918 to 1922.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He was minister of the Free Christian Church in Leicester and of Dover Unitarian Church from 1933 to 1939.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He joined the Vegetarian Society in 1894 and became their lecturer in 1897.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He advocated for a vegetarian diet consisting of whole bread, nuts, soups, omelettes, coffee and fruit.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] In 1912, Broadley was a speaker at Vegetarian Society meeting in Plymouth with Alfred B.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He commented that he had been a vegetarian for 21 years which had made him a happier man without visit to a doctor.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He also lectured on "Vegetarianism and the Higher Life", expounding the thesis that "any relationship to living creatures not based upon love, is contrary to conscience and will of God".
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] Broadley conducted the memorial service for William E.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] Axon's funeral at St Paul's Church, Kersal Moor in January 1913.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] He was a delegate of the Vegetarian Society to the Fourth Congress of the International Vegetarian Union in June 1913.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] Broadley was an opponent of vivisection.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] In 1923, he attended an anti-vivisection meeting with members from the British Union for the Abolition of Vivisection in Preston.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] Broadley died on 25 April 1939 from a heart attack at his residence in Dover, aged 70.
[src:arnold-hills/a-o-broadley] His funeral was held at St James's Cemetery.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills was born in Denmark Hill, Surrey, on 12 March 1857, the son of Frank Clarke Hills, a manufacturing chemist, and Ann Ellen Hills (née Rawlings).
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills was a British mile champion, winning the 1878 AAC Championships title, and was the three-mile champion in 1879.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] In his youth, he played football and cricket for Harrow School, where he captained the first XI.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] After leaving Harrow, he attended University College, Oxford, where he earned a B.A. in 1880 and two football blues.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He played as a forward for Oxford University when the team finished runners-up to Wanderers in the 1877 FA Cup Final.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] After leaving Oxford, Hills continued to play as an amateur for Old Harrovians and received a Corinthian's Cap while with the club.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He played once for England, against Scotland on 5 April 1879 at the Kennington Oval, in a 5–4 England win.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills was managing director of the Thames Iron Works, a shipbuilding business in London that had existed since 1846.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He lived for five years among his workers in a small house in East India Dock Road in Canning Town and organised recreational centres for them.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He also caused resentment during a strike over pay and working conditions by employing strikebreakers.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] In the summer of 1895, Hills and Dave Taylor helped found Thames Ironworks F.C., which later became West Ham United.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills wanted the local community to have its own football team and financially supported the club until April 1900.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] After disagreements with West Ham's board over professionalism, he ended his formal ties with the club and the Thames Ironworks.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills proposed that West Ham be formed as a limited company and became its major shareholder.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He encouraged business associates, family members, and his workers to invest, promising to buy one share for every share sold to the public.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He rented the Memorial Grounds to the club on favourable terms.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills told the new directors that he would not interfere in the running of the club and, despite being its largest single shareholder, did not attend annual general meetings, ask to address meetings, or present demands or suggestions.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills was the first president of the London Vegetarian Society, founded in 1888, and served on its executive committee with the young Mahatma Gandhi.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He was also the first president of the Vegetarian Cycling and Athletic Club and president of the London Vegetarian Rambling Club.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He founded *The Vegetarian*, an independent periodical, and the Vegetarian Federal Union in 1889, of which he was also president.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He founded the Oriolet Fruitarian Hospital at Loughton, under the medical direction of Josiah Oldfield.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] In an article titled "Milk and Eggs", Hills described milk, cream, butter, cheese, and eggs as "props of a transition period" rather than part of the vegetarian ideal.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He argued that milk and eggs were foods naturally intended for young animals and human infants, and that adults should move beyond them.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He criticised the use of milk, cream, butter, and especially cheese on physiological grounds, claiming that cheese was made indigestible by fermentation.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Hills also rejected eggs as less digestible when cooked, and said that reliance on milk and eggs was justified only by social convenience.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He urged vegetarian "experimentalists" to replace them with fruit, nuts, and grains.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] In 1892, Hills authored *Vital Food*, in which he argued for a plant-based raw food diet.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] The failing fortunes of the ironworks and Hills's involvement in developing a new car engine pushed the club into the background, and he became disabled due to arthritis.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] He died at Hammerfield, Penshurst, Kent, in 1927, aged 69, and was buried at St Luke's Church in Penshurst.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] His shareholding in West Ham, 1,100 of 4,000 shares, passed to his family; 1,142 shares remained unsold until 1961.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] Forward's 1898 history of vegetarianism, *Fifty Years of Food Reform*, was dedicated to Hills.
[src:arnold-hills/arnold-hills] In 2014, as part of its preparations for moving to the Olympic Stadium, West Ham announced that one of its corporate entertainment areas would be a private dining club named the Arnold Hills suite.
